er, thereby restricting the issues and solutions that they discuss. While the American demographic profile is changing, rhetoric that links American identity with racially coded concepts and appeals to white voters' racial resentments has become ubiquitous. Angelo warns us about the possible repercussions of such tactics, noting that, while they may allow presidents to craft winning coalitions, their use continues to legitimate a system that ignores racial inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication in politics-Social aspects-United States. 0aPolitical oratory-United States. 0aPresidents-United States-Election-History-20th century. 0aPresidents-United States-Election-History-21st century. 0aPresidents-United States-Racial attitudes. 0aRhetoric-Political aspects-United States. 0aUnited States-Politics and government-1945-1989. 0aUnited States-Politics and government-1989-. 0aUnited States-Race relations-Political aspects-History-20th century. 0aUnited States-Race relations-Political aspects-History-21st century. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aHistory : American History. 4aPolitics and Law : American Politics. 4aPolitics and Law : Presidency, The. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438471532423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438471532/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles